'''Physics of financial markets''' is a discipline that studies [[financial markets]] from the perspective of [[physics]]. It seeks to understand the nature of financial processes and phenomena by employing the [[scientific method]] and avoiding beliefs, unverifiable assumptions and immeasurable notions, not uncommon to finance and economic disciplines. Physics of financial markets addresses issues such issues as theory of price formation,<ref name="Jack2013">J. Sarkissian (2013), [https://arxiv.org/abs/1312.4622 "Coupled mode theory of stock price formation"].</ref><ref>J. Sarkissian (April, 2016), [https://arxiv.org/abs/1605.04948 "Quantum Theory of Securities Price Formation in Financial Markets"]. Available at SSRN: http://ssrn.com/abstract=2765298</ref><ref>J. Sarkissian (June, 2016), [https://arxiv.org/abs/1606.07381 "Spread, volatility, and volume relationship in financial markets and market making profit optimization"]. Available at SSRN: http://ssrn.com/abstract=2799798</ref><ref>J. Sarkissian, "Option pricing under quantum theory of securities price formation" (October 4, 2016). Available at SSRN: http://ssrn.com/abstract=2848014</ref> price dynamics,<ref name="Jack2013" /><ref>Vadim A Nastasiuk (2014) [https://arxiv.org/abs/1312.3247 "Emergent quantum mechanics of finances"], Physica A: Statistical Mechanics and its Applications, Vol. 403, 148-154.</ref><ref>V.A. Nastasiuk (2015) [https://arxiv.org/pdf/1504.03822v1.pdf "Fisher information and quantum potential well model for finance"], Physics Letters A Vol. 379, Issue 36, 25 September 2015, Pages 1998–2000.</ref> market [[ergodicity]],<ref>J. Sarkissian, "[http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2812353 Express Measurement of Market Volatility Using Ergodicity Concept]" (July 20, 2016). Available at SSRN: <nowiki>http://ssrn.com/abstract=2812353</nowiki></ref><ref>O. Peters, W. Klein, “[https://arxiv.org/abs/1209.4517 Ergodicity breaking in geometric Brownian motion]”, Phys. Rev. Lett. 110, 100603 (2013)</ref><ref>O. Peters, “[[arxiv:0902.2965|Optimal leverage from non-ergodicity]]”, Quantitative Finance, Volume 11, Issue 11, (2011)</ref><ref>F. Lillo, R.N. Mantegna, “[[arxiv:cond-mat/0006065|Variety and volatility in financial markets]]”, Phys. Rev. E 62, 6126–6134 (2000)</ref> collective phenomena, self-action, and market instabilities. Physics of financial markets should not be confused for [[Mathematical finance|quantitative finance]] and [[econophysics]], which are only concerned with modeling financial instruments without seeking to understand nature of underlying processes.
