{{orphan|date=August 2013}} <!--- Don't mess with this line! ---> <!--- Replace Subject of my article with the subject, and the ... after is with whatever your subject is. ---> The '''thermomechanical cuttings cleaner (TCC)''' is a patented technology mainly used by service providers in the [[oil and gas industry]] to separate and recover the components of oil-contaminated drilling waste.<ref name="Clean team">{{cite news|title=The clean team|url=http://www.europeanoilandgas.co.uk/article-page.php?contentid=18061&issueid=501|accessdate=21 August 2013|newspaper=European Oil & Gas|date=4 July 2013}}</ref> A TCC converts [[kinetic energy]] to [[thermal energy]] in a thermal desorption process which efficiently transforms drilling waste into re-usable products.<ref name=Mypaper>{{cite news|title=Thermal separation technology|url=http://www.mypaper.se/show/text.asp?pid=345154162864355&page=102|accessdate=21 August 2013|newspaper=Norway Exports - Oil & Gas|page=100|year=2007}}</ref> Using kinetic energy instead of indirect heating allows for very short retention times and as a consequence the quality of the separated components is not affected by the treatment. Thus the recovered water, base oil and solids can be re-used after the treatment process.<ref name="Drilling Contractor">{{cite news|last=Mazerov|first=Katie|title=Bulk tanks, thermal systems advance environmental efficiency of cuttings handling|url=http://www.drillingcontractor.org/bulk-tanks-thermal-systems-advance-environmental-efficiency-of-cuttings-handling-11047|accessdate=21 August 2013|newspaper=Drilling Contractor|date=26 September 2011}}</ref>
